<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.ussnautilus.org/images/571A.JPG"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
<br>
Science fiction was in the cultural air in the 19th century, but it wasn't until the first quarter of the 20th century that the genre acquired a name of its own to distinguish it from mainstream literature. <br>
<br>
Mainstream literature has always included a variety of fantasy and fantastic types of stories -- including some we would today call science fiction -- from its inception in oral tales told around campfires. <br>
<br>
In the 19th century, as science itself began its transformation of the world, authors brought a new element to their fantastic tales: the sense of realistic possibility they gained from speculative scientific trappings. <br>
<br>
Verne and Wells<br>
<br>
The two 19th century authors most associated with science fiction today, the Frenchman Jules Verne and English author Herbert George Wells, called their novels &quot;Extraordinary Voyages,&quot; and &quot;Scientific Romances&quot; respectively. Verne's novelistic voyages to the center of the earth, the moon, and around the world were the very stuff of self fulfilling prophesy. They inspired many. Some of them the greatest minds of our time.<br>
